    "blocks": [
      {
        "id": "title",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "# Hopper: Curvature vs Standard ES Without Trust Rescaling"
      },
      {
        "id": "technical_summary",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Technical summary\n\nThe clean mentor-requested comparison is complete. Across two decreasing learning-rate schedules and two large initial rates, the signed diagonal frozen-rank curvature surrogate does **not** reliably improve Standard ES. The apparent gain in one cell is not seed-consistent. The mechanism diagnostics separate the failure cleanly: diagonal division is numerically accurate, but the curvature estimate is non-repeatable and creates severely ill-conditioned update denominators. Trust-radius rescaling, replay, Picard iteration, damping, and clipping are absent from this experiment."
      },
      {
        "id": "headline_metrics",
        "type": "metric-strip",
        "cardIds": [
          "validated_runs",
          "supported_cells",
          "split_sign",
          "max_amplification"
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "performance_finding",
        "type": "markdown",
        "sourceId": "paired_contrasts_json",
        "body": "## Curvature does not consistently improve the primary metric\n\nMean AUC is slightly higher for curvature in both inverse-square-root cells and lower in both inverse-linear cells. None of the four paired comparisons is consistent across seeds: win counts range from 4/10 to 6/10, and every exact two-sided sign-flip p-value is at least 0.369. The chart compares absolute means; its large curvature spread at `alpha_0=10` under the inverse-square-root schedule is an immediate warning against interpreting the mean alone."
      },
      {
        "id": "mean_auc_chart",
        "type": "chart",
        "chartId": "mean_auc_comparison",
        "layout": "full"
      },
      {
        "id": "pairing_finding",
        "type": "markdown",
        "sourceId": "paired_contrasts_json",
        "body": "## Seed pairing exposes the outlier behind the largest apparent gain\n\nFor `alpha_0=10` with `alpha_t = alpha_0/sqrt(t+1)`, the mean paired gain is +8.322 but the paired median is -8.820 and curvature wins only 4/10 seeds. Seed 9 contributes +119.661 AUC, reversing the sign of the average. The distribution view therefore supports the conservative conclusion: there is no robust curvature advantage in this matrix."
      },
      {
        "id": "paired_distribution_chart",
        "type": "chart",
        "chartId": "paired_auc_distribution",
        "layout": "full"
      },
      {
        "id": "exact_results_finding",
        "type": "markdown",
        "sourceId": "paired_contrasts_json",
        "body": "## Exact cell results agree with the distribution view\n\nThe paired mean, median, sample standard deviation, wins, and exact randomization p-value all point in the same direction: positive means are small or outlier-sensitive, while the inverse-linear cells are neutral to negative. These are exploratory cellwise tests, not a multiplicity-adjusted confirmatory family."
      },
      {
        "id": "paired_results_table",
        "type": "table",
        "tableId": "paired_auc_table",
        "layout": "full"
      },
      {
        "id": "scope_definitions",
        "type": "markdown",
        "sourceId": "protocol_document",
        "body": "## Scope and metric definitions\n\nThe study uses Hopper-v5, 200 fresh antithetic candidates per update, 500 updates, and ten paired seeds for every schedule/rate cell. The schedules are `alpha_t = alpha_0/sqrt(t+1)` and `alpha_t = alpha_0/(t+1)`, with `alpha_0` in {10, 30}. The primary metric is online evaluation-return AUC through 75,000 **actual training environment steps**, using linear interpolation at the boundary; evaluation rollouts are excluded from that budget. The curvature arm solves the signed diagonal linearization `delta_j = alpha_t g_j / (1 - alpha_t h_j)`. Because `h_j` comes from centered within-batch ranks held fixed in the linearization, the precise name is **signed diagonal frozen-rank curvature surrogate**, not raw-return Hessian."
      },
      {
        "id": "methodology",
        "type": "markdown",
        "sourceId": "protocol_document",
        "body": "## Experimental controls isolate curvature from step-norm rescaling\n\nStandard ES and curvature use the same environment, policy architecture, population size, noise scale, observation-normalization protocol, schedule, initial rate, and paired seed. Replay, importance sampling, endpoint Picard iteration, trust radius, fixed-norm updates, scalar damping, L2, gradient clipping, parameter projection, curvature projection, curvature clipping, and curvature EMA are disabled. The validator checks the complete 80-cell task map, every scheduled learning-rate value, 500-record histories, fresh-only sampling, source-lock provenance, and signed-system arithmetic before emitting the result files."
      },
      {
        "id": "mechanism_finding",
        "type": "markdown",
        "sourceId": "validated_runs_csv",
        "body": "## Accurate division cannot rescue a non-repeatable curvature estimate\n\nThe maximum relative division residual is below 5e-17, so the elementwise arithmetic is not the failure. In contrast, split-half and temporal correlations are approximately zero, coordinate sign agreement is approximately 50%, the smallest absolute denominator reaches 6.29e-9, and one update is amplified by more than one million times relative to the explicit ES step. The evidence supports estimator-induced ill-conditioning of the signed system."
      },
      {
        "id": "mechanism_results_table",
        "type": "table",
        "tableId": "mechanism_table",
        "layout": "full"
      },
      {
        "id": "limitations",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Limitations and robustness boundary\n\nThis is a clean basic comparison, not a universal test of curvature-informed ES. The 5,123-coordinate surrogate is estimated from only 100 antithetic pairs, and the very large updates move far outside the perturbation scale, so estimator noise and local-linearization error cannot be fully separated by return curves alone. Online evaluation uses three fixed episodes and is less stringent than the later 20-episode held-out confirmation. Exact cellwise p-values are descriptive because the four cells were not registered as a jointly adjusted confirmatory family. The completed run artifacts are tied to the archived source digest; the current worktree is newer and any rerun needs a new source lock."
      },
      {
        "id": "next_steps",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Recommended next steps\n\n1. Share this negative basic result and the estimator-versus-arithmetic diagnosis with the mentor; do not reuse the trust-confounded plots.\n2. Before another environment sweep, require a curvature estimator to show materially positive split-batch agreement on frozen Hopper checkpoints.\n3. Compare any stabilized structured estimator against both Standard ES and a norm-matched isotropic attenuation control, without trust clipping.\n4. Add an explicit locality diagnostic such as `||delta_t||/sigma` so future work can separate estimator reliability from Taylor-remainder failure."
      },
      {
        "id": "further_questions",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Further questions\n\n- How many independent antithetic pairs are needed before the signed curvature components become repeatable at Hopper dimension?\n- Does lower-dimensional block or subspace curvature retain directional information beyond generic attenuation?\n- At frozen checkpoints, does prediction error track update locality, denominator resonance, or both?\n- Can a matched-rank implicit formulation be derived whose gradient and curvature estimators are finite-population compatible?"
      }
    ]
  },
